ro healing is really nice, but not quite that nice. Firstly, it essentially requires constant combat in order to work, which is great for those 15 minute fights when everyone is two bubbles down and VLOM for the last 10, and in fact, those were my favorite times in EQ. But, if you can't have a constant flow of meaningful lifetap damage, it falls over. <P>Pact/Shadowbond also have recast times you aren't including, and Lich isn't quite -tha- godly, it's 32 HP for 20 mana, not 32. <P>But yes, necromancers can do some awe inspiring things in fights they haven't been systematically prevented from participating in.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">zondro</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Vanya is correct, it is impossible to get near the heal ratio this person claims.  A necro cannot top celestial cleansing.  Also, stacking pacts on ONE person does nothing.  And in most groups there is only 1 tank taking the damage.  Basically pact is a dot on necro and heal dot on target.  You only get super good healing efficiancy when you have multiple targets to hit with that heal dot, while the necro is only taking damage from one dot.  Aslo it is impossible to stack shadowbond on more than one target.<P>I would like to add that necroes are HIGHLY underrated in groups.  Yes, Clr/chanter/warrior are the staples.  But if you add a necro to that holy trinity I guarantee you will find safetly levels going up and efficiency going WAY up.  Well.. a good necro that is.<P>I know a lot of plain dumbass necroes that dont even use lich, they sit in c2 and just send pets, cast snare and mana pump the cleric.  I highly encourage you to boot this necro from your group and send him back to skyfire.<P>a few other mistakes in this guide:  Lich is not 32:32.  it's 32:20.  And yes it works when you are standing, but c2 works while standing as well, so it's not a big deal.  (although, any necro that prefers c2 is a fool)</FONT><